commit_message:
Add documentation for HA ceilometer

HA ceilometer can work if the proper overrides
are configured. This patch adds documentation
regarding running ceilometer in an active/active
HA configuration, meaning workload paritioning
can be done across multiple polling agents and
notification agents.

Change-Id: I65402a66f465df8dc82a24460531fba3a24a8cf5
Closes-Bug: #1518005
(cherry picked from commit 5371a0eb93ff088e8f26fef698ff7fcae95a58fa)

subject: Use PyPi packages for ceph python bindings
messages:
[{'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:48:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-11-13 14:02:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for your work on this Hugh, but I'm not sure this commit as is is sufficient.  For example, the ceph_client role still installs ceph packages, and a user may assume that if they set `ceph_stable_release` they'll actually get that version installed.  This change makes it so that we'll only ever install v0.94.5-1, which _may_ be OK but I don't know enough about ceph to say for sure.  :)

Also -- how do we keep https://github.com/hughsaunders/python-cephlibs updated?  That is a manual process and in the long term may be setting us up for failure."}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-11-13 14:02:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-11-13 14:40:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hey Matt, 
Thanks for reviewing. Installing ceph packages is still required because the pip package only contains the python bindings, not the underlying c libs. As for versions, we're only supporting ceph LTSs and there hasn't been a new LTS since hammer. I hope that the official ceph pypy packages will be available before the next LTS, but if not I can upload a new version."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-13 14:59:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-openstack-ansible-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-docs/bd4099c//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 04s
- gate-openstack-ansible-lint http://logs.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-lint/450c63d/ : SUCCESS in 3m 06s
- gate-openstack-ansible-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-pep8/4219815/ : SUCCESS in 35s
- gate-openstack-ansible-bashate http://logs.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-bashate/9eb7a08/ : SUCCESS in 37s
- gate-openstack-ansible-commit-nv http://logs.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-commit-nv/7fcbff7/ : SUCCESS in 1h 09m 30s (non-voting)
- gate-openstack-ansible-dsvm-commit http://logs.openstack.org/54/245154/1/check/gate-openstack-ansible-dsvm-commit/bda6b03/ : SUCCESS in 1h 08m 10s'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-11-14 12:00:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I have worries about potential namespace conflicts in the future should redhat / ceph get the relevant packages on to pypi. That said, if there are good ways to work around this then I'm all for it however I suspect we'll run into issues in the near future. Is there an upstream git resource that we can build these package from without "vendoring" the packages?'}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-11-16 12:52:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hey Kevin,  redhat/ceph introducing an official packages is the best possible outcome - Then I can delete my package and we switch over to using the official one. No complexity added to OSAD and no package maintenance to do. However the ticket for that has been open for a while.'}, {'account_id': 7219, 'date': '2015-11-16 13:35:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think that the Python venvs should be kept separate from the host, the use of symlinking creates the type of technical debt that is hard to remove because it is interwoven with the other code and seems to be defeating the purpose of a venv. The use of a package means that this issue is reduced to having an appropriate pip package. The package can be overridden and can be updated when an official version becomes available. If the project updates the version of the Ceph client libraries it is using, a new version of the pip package can be created.

Hugh, I think it would be worth adding a link to the upstream bug tracking the creation of the package and documenting this in the roles.'}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-11-16 18:47:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Use PyPi packages for ceph python bindings

Ceph python bindings are now available from pypi, so they can be
installed within a venv. Previously we were relying on the bindings
being installed via an apt package and symlinking out of the relevant
venvs into site packages.

This commit also includes a revert for the commit that introduced the
symlinks:

Revert "Symlink ceph libraries out of venv"

This reverts commit a0ab6f7a6efea1dabf5ac006f766c17596a0d10b.

Ceph Bug: http://tracker.ceph.com/issues/5900
Related-Bug: #1509837
Package URL: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-cephlibs/0.94.5.post1

Change-Id: Id8a0b8ea810fd9e43f9743bb2572e2b6b0985230

commit_message:
Decoupling magnum service from periodic task

Liberty tech-debt-bug

Magnum service was initially utilizing periodic task within magnum
conductor. This commit lays out independent periodic framework for
magnum service, by decoupling from periodic task.

Change-Id: Ie0e725b75069309a9fa783f77c1a454f9dae549e
Partial-Bug: 1500998

commit_message:
Remove py26 support

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: Ia00d0c10d8694e331eb0690933268b952e0565dd
Closes-Bug: 1519510
Depends-On: Id93b7af9cc3ed548b78e9b08528e18e9c0383c7a

commit_message:
Change DIB role to default to Debian jessie

In the event that Debian is selected or defaulted to for an image
build operation, then that image should be jessie based.

Added logic to check and set if so, and permit user override.

Change-Id: I2c54cd4ec11fe85c246c25c3bcc219a22ef26b12

commit_message:
Removed old (and unused) openstack/oslo libs

Since all oslo libs are now using the new versions installed using
pip, there is no need to keep the watcher/openstack/common/ folder.

Implements: blueprint make-watcher-use-graduated-oslo-lib
Change-Id: I9e08b4a50c6b15a4d51a7f53fdd615d6c28fdce7

(5 comments)

This is an *ok* addition, although I'm not sure if any of these code-paths are particularly sensitive or likely to regress.

OTOH, there's some under-lying problems with this test module's schizophrenic monkey-patch-to-mock strategy that are undoubtably increasing cognitive overhead maintaining the module.  I'd probably rather see focus on cleaning up the overall strategy for testing the module  before adding new tests of marginal value that will increase the maintenance burden.

Generally I don't care for how nosetest runners replace the test name with the doc string when running in verbose mode.  I think it's almost always better to give the test a better (longer) name than to duplicate information in the doc string.  If the test requires additional context about the setup and strategy inline comments are best.  If it *still* really needs a doc string to grok it's probably too obfuscated to be a good test (google about for DAMP vs. DRY testing strategy)."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-11-04 23:22:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Added unit tests to recon.py.

Added tests for unrecognized recon_types for get_replication_info,
get_updater_info, and get_auditor_info.

Added tests for get_device_info and get_swift_conf_md5.

PEP8 compliance fixes.

Updates based on code reviews.

Change-Id: I3f636955b253ea7f65d4a1f333a0ad24f1ea6a1f

commit_message:
Add Backup & Restore feature for CouchDB database

Even though Trove supports backup and restore capabilities, this
feature hasnt been implemented for CouchDB. This spec provides
details regarding how to do backups and restore operation for
CouchDB.

Change-Id: Ie70a353d264bf2f0436deeb76200c5cf5977151d
Implements: blueprint couchdb-backup-restore

commit_message:
Removing SQL Schema Downgrade

Following a cross-project spec [1] we are supposed to remove
downgrade methods from migration files.

Change-Id: I9979a23d412e33856ca214b1807d8659f136ef88
Related: blueprint https://blueprints.launchpad.net/trove/+spec/remove-sql-schema-downgrades

commit_message:
Postgresql streaming replication

Spec outlining the use of the out-of-the-box replication
support in pgsql based on streaming WAL data.

Implements: blueprint pgsql-replication
Change-Id: Ic9ee323a6d82e3032fb9d31ad2a898844239c821

commit_message:
Wake up AMT interface before send request

AMT interface goes to sleep after a period of time if the host
is off. Add a new method 'awake_amt_interface' for amt driver
to awake nodes' AMT interface.
This method will ping AMT interface to to wake it up before sending
request. Also set 60s by default as cache time.

Change-Id: I4d81001c01e7908100a6571b366cb296253f2fc1
Close-bug: #1504023

Fix No module named importlib in python-*client

keystoneclient use importlib, and the gate failed to import it in
python2.6 env. Cause gate error with *No module named importlib*.

One of the missing features in Flavors which is supposed to be addressed by flavors is the option to "piggyback" additional metadata with the flavor that can be passed to the provider.
For example, GOLD = high capacity load balancer and SILVER = medium capacity. Both flavors may use the same provider albeit providing different "information" to the provider so it knows that it needs to provide the appropriate service.
I do not see this addressed here.'}, {'account_id': 12999, 'date': '2015-11-20 18:49:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-14 17:34:38.000000000', 'message': "Add flavor option to loadbalancerv2 creation

Builds on the Neutron services flavor framework in the referenced
Depends-On change id.

This solution uses a flavor of service type LOADBALANCERV2
associated with a flavor profile containing a driver.  If a
flavor_id is passed during loadbalancerv2 creation, the flavor is
used to find the provider for the driver and populate
the existing lbaas provider field.

This allows a user to specify a flavor like 'Gold' with the
operator dynamically controlling which provider is associated
with that flavor for subsequent creates.

The flavor_id is persisted in the DB with a foreign key reference
to the flavors.id, and for this solution the selected provider
controls subsequent control operations against the created
loadbalancer.

To enable multiple providers in DevStack, enhanced the plugin.sh
and settings to add a secondary service provider.

Change-Id: Ic3b459692d092658df93d4c855079311d9bc7ace
Depends-On: I5c22ab655a8e2a2e586c10eae9de9b72db49755f
Implements: blueprint neutron-flavor-framework

"}, {'created': '2015-11-24 17:34:06.000000000', 'message': "Add flavor option to loadbalancerv2 creation

Depends-On change id.

This solution uses a flavor of service type LOADBALANCERV2
associated with a flavor profile containing a driver.  If a
flavor_id is passed during loadbalancerv2 creation, the flavor is
used to find the provider for the driver and populate
the existing lbaas provider field.

This allows a user to specify a flavor like 'Gold' with the
operator dynamically controlling which provider is associated
with that flavor for subsequent creates.

The flavor_id is persisted in the DB.  The selected provider
controls subsequent control operations against the created
loadbalancer.

To enable multiple providers in DevStack for testing since defaults
to single Octavia reference provider, enhance devstack/plugin.sh
and settings to add one or more secondary lbaas service providers
in the Octavia tree.

Also ensure everything works gracefully if flavors plugin is not loaded.

Adding api and doc impact tags as the new optional flavor_id parameter
should be described to consumers.

commit_message:
Add flavor option to loadbalancerv2 creation

Builds on the Neutron services flavor framework in the referenced
Depends-On change id.

This solution uses a flavor of service type LOADBALANCERV2
associated with a flavor profile containing a driver.  If a
flavor_id is passed during loadbalancerv2 creation, the flavor is
used to find the provider for the driver and populate
the existing lbaas provider field.

This allows a user to specify a flavor like 'Gold' with the
operator dynamically controlling which provider is associated
with that flavor for subsequent creates.

The flavor_id is persisted in the DB.  The selected provider
controls subsequent control operations against the created
loadbalancer.

Also ensure everything works gracefully if flavors plugin is not loaded.

Adding api and doc impact tags as the new optional flavor_id parameter
should be described to consumers.

Co-Authored-By: James Arendt <james.arendt@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Madhusudhan Kandadai <madhusudhan.kandadai@hpe.com>

ApiImpact
DocImpact
Change-Id: Ic3b459692d092658df93d4c855079311d9bc7ace
Depends-On: I5c22ab655a8e2a2e586c10eae9de9b72db49755f
Partially implements: blueprint neutron-flavor-framework

commit_message:
[install] Fix Ceilometer Debian install

This patch fixes the Ceilometer Debian install, by adding Debian
to a few conditionals, and removing some parts which aren't needed
in Debian.

Change-Id: If2234cb6000a86c3ac2d2309df3fd2fef9cc9927

commit_message:
Enable all extension for image API sample tests

As extensions options has been deprecated, API sample tests
should run against all extension enable.

This commit enables all extensions for Image API tests and remove its specific
extensions tests and sample files.
Also adds some basic hack to merge all APIs tests for all extension.

Partially implements blueprint api-sample-tests-with-all-extensions

Change-Id: Ib603fbccfdc09b25d4c69c872d79e4cafc30fff5

commit_message:
Add better input checking for MongoDB

A user-create on the Trove admin user "admin.os_admin" can change the
password of that user, rendering the guest agent useless (the password
it tries to use no longer being valid).

A user-create can also be used to change the password of existing users.

The guest does no validation of inputs for various user-* commands.

None of the above should be allowed.

The fix is to skip any names on the ignored user's list and add more
checking for existing users in codepaths.

Tests are also updated as needed.

Change-Id: Icae98f57f7beda23e52b7e59a1a386c03ff20cf8
Closes-bug: 1517622

commit_message:
Add detail view for baymodel

This patch adds detail view for baymodel into baymodel panel.
Detail view is linked from baymodel table view and other panel.

This patch is with reference to the following patch.
- https://review.openstack.org/173885/

Partially Implements: blueprint bay-model-detail-view

Change-Id: Iab44a5cd56e349decbab3d6871bd86f2b010193c

subject: [Verify] Fixing issue with create_isolated_networks = False

commit_message:
[Verify] Fixing issue with create_isolated_networks = False

If you take a look at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/229623/ and the
corresponding test run [1], you will see that 70 tempest tests failed.
It is because the create_isolated_networks flag is set to False. The
wrong option value was introduced by the mentioned patch. We don't
need to set the value for the option because we have the corresponding
Tempest context that uses the following logic:

    if the cloud doesn't have any shared networks, the default behavior
    defined in Tempest will be used and Tempest itself will manage network
    resources, i.e Tempest will create networks, subnets, routers, etc;

    if the cloud has some shared networks, we will create our own shared
    network and specify its name in the Tempest config file to avoid the
    "Multiple possible networks found." error;

    if user configures the fixed_network_name option in the tempest.conf
    file manually, then we don't need to do anything.

So we should remove create_isolated_networks = False from the config.ini
file to fix the issue.

Also we should use use_dynamic_credentials = True instead of allow_tenant_
isolation = True because this option is deprecated [2].

[1] http://logs.openstack.org/23/229623/3/gate/gate-rally-dsvm-verify-full/3921e9c/rally-verify/7_verify_results_--html.html.gz
[2] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/config.py#L63

Change-Id: I4fe74bf6b4f12fc09ba94f3bef68c304630a848f

commit_message:
Reorganize documentation

This patch reorgs the documentation structure. After this reorg, the top
level structure becomes:

  - overview
  - install
  - getting started
  - contributing to Senlin
  - glossary
  - man pages

commit_message:
Make asynchronous action return 202

In senlin the actions are executed asynchronously, according to
api-wg, asynchronous action should return 202 instead of 200
status code to client to confirm the request.
This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: Idd9e139844073c3dfa79990a9426ae2973367627
Implements: blueprint http-response-modification

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

This cycle, to address these problems for our ever-growing set of
projects, the release management team is introducing a new tool for
handling release notes as files in-tree, to allow us to simply and
continuously build the release notes for stable branch point releases
and milestones on the master branch. The idea is to use small YAML
files, usually one per note or patch, to avoid merge conflicts on
backports and then to compile those files in a deterministic way
into a more readable document for readers. Files containing release
notes can be including in patches directly, or you can create a
separate patch with release notes if you want to document a feature
than spans several patches.  The tool is called Reno, and it currently
supports ReStructuredText and Sphinx for converting note input files
to HTML for publication.  Reno is git branch-aware, so we can have
separate release notes documents for each release series published
together from the master build.

-- Excerpted from Doug Hellmann's email to the mailing list
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078301.html

For more information about Reno:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/reno/

Change-Id: I4028d52f5e67d2873b3dc9df279f78a15c35d84f

commit_message:
Fix fixed_ip schema and service client

There are two issues in fixed_ip schema and client.
1. Schema expect string in response body-
   Nova had bug#1356058 for response of reserve/unreserve fixed ip APIs,
   where plain text ("202 Accepted The request is accepted for processing.")
   was returned in response body.
   It is fixed on Nova side - Ifca3081f573407808a2196e71ac1db87180db6ec

2. Return value of reserve_fixed_ip client method-
    In Fixed ip service client, reserve_fixed_ip method does not
    return the response body.
    As per consistency in service client interfaces, this method should
    return the response value even that is empty body.

Those were fixed in Tempest but did not get sync in lib.
-I098ee0d1fa3056f8cfb0654e2b8fd3bf75fb3e2c
-I2cb1ef8dacd1994576656cfb108dd2eef2fbd988

Change-Id: I27b8d2165188ee069f5d8d22c0426f2c748f80c8

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-05 15:37:09.000000000', 'message': "VMware: add in vnic resource limitations

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:vnic_limit - The bandwidth limit for the virtual network adapter.
                    The utilization of the virtual network adapter will not
                    exceed this limit, even if there are available resources.
                    Units in Mbits/sec.
 quota:vnic_reservation - Amount of network bandwidth that is guaranteed to
                          the virtual network adapter. If utilization is less
                          than reservation, the resource can be used by other
                          virtual network adapters. Reservation is not allowed
                          to exceed the value of limit if limit is set.
                          Units in Mbits/sec.

Shares: Network share. The value is used as a relative weight in competing for
        shared bandwidth, in case of resource contention.

 quota:vnic_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                          'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:vnic_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                          number of shares.

This enables the VMware driver to enable VNIC allocations
for the running instance.

WIP - still need to add unit tests

DocImpact

Change-Id: Id321ffcb17114b53141f2489156869d418b768fd

 quota:vif_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                          'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:vif_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                          number of shares.

Please see http://goo.gl/c2amhq for a detailed explanation of the above.

This enables the VMware driver to enable VNIC allocations
for the running instance.

commit_message:
VMware: add in vif resource limitations

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:vif_limit - The bandwidth limit for the virtual network adapter.
                   The utilization of the virtual network adapter will not
                   exceed this limit, even if there are available resources.
                   Units in Mbits/sec.
 quota:vif_reservation - Amount of network bandwidth that is guaranteed to
                         the virtual network adapter. If utilization is less
                         than reservation, the resource can be used by other
                         virtual network adapters. Reservation is not allowed
                         to exceed the value of limit if limit is set.
                         Units in Mbits/sec.

Shares: Network share. The value is used as a relative weight in competing for
        shared bandwidth, in case of resource contention.

 quota:vif_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                          'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:vif_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                             number of shares.

Please see http://goo.gl/c2amhq for a detailed explanation of the above.

This enables the VMware driver to enable VNIC allocations
for the running instance.

NOTE: this is only supported from vCenter 6.0 onwards.

Co-Authored-By: Radoslav Gerganov <rgerganov@vmware.com>
DocImpact

This is part of the blueprint vmware-limits-mitaka

commit_message:
add hacking check for config options location

This adds a hackign check which raises a pep8 error if a config
option was found in location where it shouldn't be.

Change-Id: I75df3404cc6178aa179e96d75f154e389c3008af

Add symlink from akanda elemnt to new astara element.

This can be dropped when devstack plugin is updated.

"Terminate Instance" calls api.nova.server_delete and it calls server.delete() method from novaclient.  If there is a case where "Terminate Instance" cannot delete a server, the same thing applies to "nova delete" command and DELETE /servers/xxxx in Nova API.
Thus I think we can use "delete" instead.

In addition, I heard from users that they didn't think a server is deleted completely when clicking "terminate instance". They said they just thought their instances would be destroyed forcely but it was not :-(   It is not a good user experience.

Anyway I would like to hear more opinions!'}, {'account_id': 16769, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Tested and works as expected.

I think "Delete" is more understandable to most people than "Terminate".  After all, the official definition for terminate is "to bring to an end" while delete's definition is "to remove or obliterate".  I would say that in the context of an instance, we are not just bringing them to an end, we are obliterating them. ;)'}, {'account_id': 10881, 'date': '2015-10-06 22:28:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I like this change. I think Delete is a better description than Terminate.  When I first started using OpenStack I expected a Terminated instance to still be available for re-use later.'}, {'account_id': 6763, 'date': '2015-10-08 08:50:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

+1  i like the change too'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-10-12 15:05:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Did everyone on Horizon review this patch?

I think we should be looking further afield than the Horizon reviewers for this one; people in UX etc; it doesn't seem like there is a huge rush to address this, so it can definitely wait a bit for more info. This has definitely come up a number of times, and has been rejected previously. I thought that, the reason was because of nova configurations handling deletes differently, it is not always entirely removed, so "Delete" is incorrect.'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-11-16 21:13:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

DocImpact really should be required on this patch, based on David's comment."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-16 22:22:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-18 16:43:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for all comments. Let me share my thought.

- I agree that there is no need to rush this review. This is the reason I proposed this in the early stage of the dev cycle.
- UX reviewer would be appreciated.
- I also agree DocImpact flag is required. In addition, I can follow up corresponding changes in documentations in docs.o.o.
- I have a different opinion on a point that the nova can behave differently. We already use “nova delete” and “openstack server delete” in CLI for the same operation. In my view, keeping both “terminate” in Horizon and “delete” in CLI for the same operation. It is confusing to me and I heard from users several times that they thought “terminate” in Horizon does not delete their instances completely. If we keep "terminate", shouldn't we propose to rename "nova delete" to "nova terminate" for consistency, though I don't like it? I can move the discussion to the dev list if we need more input from nova, CLI, UX folks.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-11-18 18:07:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think Akhiro goals to rename this is correct. To be blunt, I think it would be a waste of time and a bad idea to go try to get the CLI to change.  Do you have any idea how many scripts (bash, puppet, chef, ansible, etc, etc) make use of this command at this point?

The classic nova CLI uses it (nova delete):
  
      delete  Immediately shut down and delete specified server(s).

The OpenStack client also has adopted that terminology"

   openstack server delete <name>


From a UX standpoint, most people will switch between CLI and UI.  A consistency in commands can't be a bad thing.

The API docs talk about deleting a server and the API is the "Delete" API.  

http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2.1.html#deleteServer

And the underlying call we are making is:

 novaclient(request).servers.delete(instance)

So, I don't see how changing this to Delete is a bad idea.  When I look at the baffling array of options in the Nova action list (pause, suspend, shelve, lock, shutoff, terminate), Delete would be very clear to me about what is going to happen.  I might look at terminate and think, hmm, that sounds closes to shutting it off... what does that really mean?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-23 11:48:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-23 11:51:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I added DocImpact flag to the commit message. I will be responsible to make the related docs changes as follow-up.

Rob, could you share a pointer that we still should not use "Delete"?
All corresponding API/CLI from Nova community use 'delete' and I don't see any reason that the dashboard sticks to "Terminate".
I hope you share more detail and this will help more detail reviews.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-23 12:44:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Replace "Terminate Instance" with "Delete Instance"

"Delete" is being used almost everywhere in OpenStack Dashboard
except the instance panel. Using "Delete" looks more consistent.
In addition, "Delete" tells non-native English speakers that
deleted instances will be no longer usable again compared to
"Terminate".

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1502773
Change-Id: Idccaf3c45566f20f11d02ada64c1d3934a6f3002

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-10 06:15:37.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanup of compute api reboot method

The interaction of between the check_instance_state decorator for
the compute api reboot method and the extra checking done within
the method for task states was confusing and in some cases
contradictory. For example although the decorator allowed
instances with a task_state of REBOOTING_HARD, in practice it
could never succed whether it was a soft or hard reboot.

Also several task states allowed by the decorator were implicitly
rejected because they were not listed in the expected task_states for
the instance save call. This too is fixed.

Change-Id: Iba24f2ed9d2d3161318b4b1fc55c0e97d7aed1c6
Closes-Bug: 1379425

instances with a task_state of REBOOTING_HARD, in practice it
could never succeed whether it was a soft or hard reboot.

Also several task states allowed by the decorator were implicitly
rejected because they were not listed in the expected task_states for
the instance save call. This too is fixed.

Change-Id: Iba24f2ed9d2d3161318b4b1fc55c0e97d7aed1c6
Closes-Bug: 1379425

commit_message:
Cleanup of compute api reboot method

The interaction between the check_instance_state decorator for
the compute api reboot method and the extra checking done within
the method for task states was confusing and in some cases
contradictory.

Also several task states allowed by the decorator were implicitly
rejected because they were not listed in the expected task_states for
the instance save call. This too is fixed.

Change-Id: Iba24f2ed9d2d3161318b4b1fc55c0e97d7aed1c6
Closes-Bug: 1379425

Also, please consider adding support of DNSSL option in the patch'}, {'account_id': 10257, 'date': '2015-11-05 13:52:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Reg: DNSSL support.

Recently as part of "Internal dns resolution" BP[1], neutron port api was enhanced to support dns_name/dns_assignment fields and the corresponding patch [2] has moved the dhcp_domain from dhcp agent config to neutron.conf [3]

During Tokyo summit, there was a session about integrating Neutron with Designate and the speakers have mentioned that they have plans to enhance the neutron net-create command to support dns_domain [4] and the plan is to add this support in the early Mitaka cycle.
Since there are some changes planned in this area, IMHO it would be better to wait until the related dns_domain changes are frozen in API/DB.
After the changes land in Neutron, we can propose a new patch which will add the DNSSL support to RADVD. Do you agree that this is sensible?

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/neutron-specs/specs/liberty/internal-dns-resolution.html
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/200952/24
[3] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/etc/neutron.conf#L118
[4] https://www.openstack.org/summit/tokyo-2015/videos/presentation/get-your-instance-by-name-integration-of-nova-neutron-and-designate (discussed at around  20:00 mins)'}, {'account_id': 10257, 'date': '2015-11-05 13:56:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-11-05 14:31:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi Sridhar, thanks for the details.

 just thought that DNS support wouldn't be complete without it. We can always make further change when the planned net-create change is in (which is always a question mark).

I'll leave the decision to the community."}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-11-05 15:24:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I don't think we need to boil the ocean and also do DNSSL support. That can be another patchset"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-05 15:26:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Support for IPv6 RDNSS Option in Router Advts

RFC6106 standardizes IPv6 Router Advertisements to support
Recursive DNS server information. RDNSS info allows an IPv6
host to configure the DNS information via RA messages without
needing DHCPv6 for the DNS configuration.

This patch configures RADVD daemon to include RDNSS entries in
the Router Advertisements when the IPv6 subnet has dns_nameservers.

Closes-Bug: #1495465
Change-Id: Ia516d40b1c7a83cd7046b2b7f42d1204f44288a9

commit_message:
Don't drop ARP table jump during OVS rewiring

The previous OVS ARP spoofing code was dropping the rule to jump to
the ARP protection table each time it was called. This call was
unnecessary since the majority of port updates are not turning
off port security.

This patch adjusts the logic to only drop the jump rule if port-sec
is disabled or if it is a network port. The existing functional tests
ensure that connectivity works as expected.

Closes-Bug: #1520013
Change-Id: I7b396d758c2d4c7e1004257d432b210bf3ee5c66
(cherry picked from commit ea4165c2af2ad5c7b5423e25c507598ebd30f7b5)

commit_message:
Don't drop ARP table jump during OVS rewiring

The previous OVS ARP spoofing code was dropping the rule to jump to
the ARP protection table each time it was called. This call was
unnecessary since the majority of port updates are not turning
off port security.

This patch adjusts the logic to only drop the jump rule if port-sec
is disabled or if it is a network port. The existing functional tests
ensure that connectivity works as expected.

Closes-Bug: #1520013
Change-Id: I7b396d758c2d4c7e1004257d432b210bf3ee5c66
(cherry picked from commit ea4165c2af2ad5c7b5423e25c507598ebd30f7b5)

commit_message:
Fix options for pluto per-peer logging

--perpeerlogbase option has no effect without --perpeerlog. [1]
Moreover there is no need to create 'logs' dir as there is a 'log'
dir that can be reused.

Also fixed indentation issue for enable_detailed_logging option
declaration.

[1] http://linux.die.net/man/8/ipsec_pluto

DocImpact
Related-Bug: #1308730
Change-Id: Ie5ef72c2abd83b9b1114d90a6c7294cc34174018
(cherry picked from commit ff49617ff7ac8f0d7268c862cc0cc4628cff9991)

Right now, we have two ways to open the modal dialog. I understand that the launch instance work was done prior to what we have today, but I would like us to reach a consensus on a single way to open up modals from a table going forward. What is missing from the wizardModalController to make it work in images?'}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-11-10 22:34:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

I don't see these as conflicting exactly.  We need to set up a similar launch context and the correct handling; if we could expect that having this is true of every such modal and that they are handled similarly, that would be nice.  But perhaps I don't understand, the wizard modal controller just places a launch context on a scope.  The purpose of this patch is to ensure that the handlers are set properly based on that launch context (what happens when you dismiss or close the modal)."}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-11-10 22:36:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

In other words, the launchContext contains information, in the case of Launch Instance, about what to do when you close the modal, contextually sensitive to where you launched it.  This would mean less in an entirely Angular world, but we have to launch instances from all kinds of places.  :)'}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2015-11-10 23:22:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27: -Code-Review

I'll remove the -1 for now. I think I understand what you're saying.... but lets talk about it on hangout. My concern is that we end up using this as a pattern in a few places when there is already one in place. But I might be misunderstanding..."}, {'account_id': 14124, 'date': '2015-11-11 14:10:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

I would suggest that we see what variation exists for different modals and then if there's a pattern that emerges, we make sure we're making the code efficient at that point."}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-17 06:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-11-24 06:29:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

This patch allows to open the Launch Instance Modal as part of the actions on the Images row.
It is used in the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/217964/ which needs it and is currently blocked waiting for this to merge.'}, {'account_id': 17013, 'date': '2015-12-02 16:07:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Patch Set 27 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-12-02 17:00:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 17:28:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Verified+1

commit_message:
Launch Instance Modal should be exist as a Service

Extracted openLaunchInstanceWizard from the
LaunchInstanceModalController to a Service named
horizon.dashboard.project.workflow.launch-instance.modal.service

This service is required for the new Images panel
to create the launch instance modal pop up.

Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table
Change-Id: Id7177cbafbfb9094d03908b5f8eba52d00241817

commit_message:
Follow-up on PyMySQL support for Red Hat platforms

Rely on packaging dependencies to avoid issues caused by different
package names between Fedora and RHEL (python-PyMySQL vs python2-PyMySQL).

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/245229/4/spec/classes/neutron_db_spec.rb
includes all the discussion that led to this.

commit_message:
Support of PyMySQL driver for MySQL backend

Add ability to use python-pymysql library as backend for MySQL
connections, and use it as default.

Update acceptance tests to use pyMySQL.

Change-Id: I625f1e6adb5ad581c293431d90d1a9e5578472d4
Docs: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PyMySQL_evaluation

subject: Follow-up on PyMySQL support for Red Hat platforms

commit_message:
Follow-up on PyMySQL support for Red Hat platforms

Rely on packaging dependencies to avoid issues caused by different
package names between Fedora and RHEL (python-PyMySQL vs
python2-PyMySQL).

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/245229/4/spec/classes/neutron_db_spec.rb
includes all the discussion that led to this.

Change-Id: I6ba84a2636411a0be76603d47ca09ee4c93fbfe6

commit_message:
Preparation for default endpoint names rename

This patch prepares for changes of default endpoint names,
so that they match default_catalog name [1].

Such change is required because recent patch [2] used correct
default values, but currently endpoint names are still created
using invalid names by defaut. This means that using just default
values of puppet-openstack modules some functionality could not
work correctly (currently migration due to Cinder will look for
'Compute Service' endpoint, but instead 'nova' endpoint is present
in DB).

Also it seems that OpenStack components moved to naming according
to default catalog long time ago [3].

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/etc/default_catalog.templates
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/219284/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141727/

Change-Id: I2a4dea90a159f1049efd1f37ef026921241f51cf
Partial-bug: #1506061

commit_message:
Ceilometer Integration

Outline an implementation for improving Trove's intergration
with Ceilometer.  New notifications will be generated for each
API call following the start|end|error pattern in use by other
Openstack projects.

Change-Id: I01856855dc614364db99d9b4855ebc1f92aa602c
Implements: blueprint ceilometer-integration

[{'created': '2015-09-15 01:41:00.000000000', 'message': 'WIP : Objects from Bay - Services

Currently k8s objects (pod/rc/service) are read from the
database. In order for native clients to work, they must
be read from the ReST bay endpoint. To execute native
clients, we must have one truth of the state of the
system, not two as we do now. This patch proposes the
change to the Service object.

Seperate patch to pass bay_uuid as a parameter to
magnum CLI will be submitted.

commit_message:
Objects from Bay - Pods

Currently k8s objects (pod/rc/service) are read from the
database. In order for native clients to work, they must
be read from the ReST bay endpoint. To execute native
clients, we must have one truth of the state of the
system, not two as we do now. This patch proposes the
change to the Pod object.

Also, please refer to the related-bug as to the temporary changes
done to make the test work for other objects namely rc,
service. These changes will be removed when the object from bay
patches for all the k8s objects are merged as part of a seperate
patch.

Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay
Related-Bug: #1502367
Related-Bug: #1504379

Change-Id: Id5be7fba2eb8622fcfeb48068728e440a0af3f5e

commit_message:
Fix RC CLI to work with Object from Bay

Fix Service CLI to work with Object from Bay changes. Pass
the --bay argument and pass the bay_identifier.

For example:
magnum rc-show <rc> --bay <bay_identifier>

Closes-Bug : #1517274
Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay

Change-Id: Ia7e51f968ea86c61ed527ee45e63ba29bf600dc4

commit_message:
Functional: Raise Exception if bay created failed.

Some time on gate, bay creation is failed, stop testing other cases which
need to be run onside a bay.

Partially implements: blueprint swarm-functional-testing
Change-Id: I48a0b0f07a7c4e5f859e44eb0cef9e629a396400

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-24 18:41:43.000000000', 'message': 'Improve metadata update operations

Currently our metadata operations in the DB and the API are less than
optimal, main issues are:

- To update metadata first we get all metadata in the API and add
  requested update metadata, then on the DB we retrieve each of the
  metadata keys and update one by one contents.
- When deletion of existing keys is requested in the DB we retrieve all
  metadata contents and for those that are not in the new metadata we
  retrieve the contents from the DB (again) and delete the entry.

This patch changes this so we no longer retrieve metadata in the API,
deletion does not retrieve any metadata from the DB and just makes 1
deletion request to the DB, and for changes we retrieve metadata once
and then issue a bulk change to create new entries and update existing
ones.

Change-Id: I12506541cca61282122e319e3504560f68df225b

commit_message:
Improve metadata update operations

Currently our metadata operations in the DB and the API are less than
optimal, main issues are:

- To update metadata first we get all metadata in the API and add
  requested update metadata, then on the DB we retrieve each of the
  metadata keys and update one by one contents.
- When deletion of existing keys is requested in the DB we retrieve all
  metadata contents and for those that are not in the new metadata we
  retrieve the contents from the DB (again) and delete the entry.

This patch changes this so we no longer retrieve metadata in the API,
deletion does not retrieve any metadata from the DB and just makes 1
deletion request to the DB, and for changes we retrieve metadata once
and then issue a bulk change to create new entries and update existing
ones.

Partial-Bug: #1238093
Change-Id: I12506541cca61282122e319e3504560f68df225b

commit_message:
Add documentation for HA ceilometer

HA ceilometer can work if the proper overrides
are configured. This patch adds documentation
regarding running ceilometer in an active/active
HA configuration, meaning workload paritioning
can be done across multiple polling agents and
notification agents.

Change-Id: I65402a66f465df8dc82a24460531fba3a24a8cf5
Closes-Bug: #1518005

commit_message:
Fixed issue with cacert parameter

We need to use parameter cacert instead of ca_file parameter
to work with CA certificates like python clients for other
OpenStack services.


Also fixed typo (after copy paste from Glance code).

(cherry picked from commit 1141dd59aff141bee6618806a4496b57c214c7c1)

Change-Id: Ibe36390aab2f2edb0fe7670f76f61caeb350d34b
Closes-Bug: #1487099

[{'created': '2015-12-02 09:09:19.000000000', 'message': "Remove py26 support

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I62db55ee1a9e7564a10a7284bd0e401b2cdbc580
Closes-Bug: 1519510
Depends-On: I4a2f860e8138bddb032418ee555e07a6fa0a3f3e
"}]
commit_message:
Remove py26 support

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I62db55ee1a9e7564a10a7284bd0e401b2cdbc580
Closes-Bug: 1519510
Depends-On: I4a2f860e8138bddb032418ee555e07a6fa0a3f3e

[{'created': '2015-12-02 18:47:33.000000000', 'message': "Use KSC auth's register_conf_options instead of oslo.cfg import

A newer keystoneclient is not happy with simply using oslo_config to
import the config group.  Instead, use register_conf_options()
from keystoneclient.auth.

Change-Id: I798dad7ad5bd90362e1fa10c2eecb3e1d5bade71
"}]
commit_message:
Use KSC auth's register_conf_options instead of oslo.cfg import

A newer keystoneclient is not happy with simply using oslo_config to
import the config group.  Instead, use register_conf_options()
from keystoneclient.auth.

Change-Id: I798dad7ad5bd90362e1fa10c2eecb3e1d5bade71

commit_message:
Disable heat-api-cloudwatch in undercloud install

By default this can be disabled, as nothing in the overcloud deployment
requires it. This will save us around 50Mb of memory in an undercloud
deployment.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I693556188460fb07df3e018402922c0a4ba2927c

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/246042/

So I think I'll just abandon this patch in favor of the cycle enumeration patch."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-11-17 22:31:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Fixed datalog cyclic dependecy inf loop bug

Purpose: remove infinite loop problem with cycle detection and enumeration

Changes:
- Added cyclic test case to tests/datalog/test_compile.py which fails pre-fix
(see patchset 1 py27 verification)
- Replaced faulty cycle enumeration facility with cycle detection facility with
a single sample cycle stored (for user feedback)

Notes:
- Full enumeration was not used by anything in the code, so I chose to implement
a simple, efficient fix without full enumeration.
- In the future, full enumeration may still be needed in the future
(eg. for detecting negative recursion)

Change-Id: Ib46ec2c422093d498d9e3d6d93327d8627bf286f

commit_message:
Fix POD CLI to work with Object from Bay

Fix POD CLI to work with Object from Bay changes. Construct
the REST URL for each API since now with Object from Bay changes
its mandatory to pass a bay identifier. Also, in the list
API explicitly pass the bay_ident for which the query is
supposed to be made. The help is also updated so that user
can see provide positional arguments.

For example:
magnum pod-show <pod-identifier> --bay <>

Change-Id: Iecc7f710d4270d2e21cae718c19307f8ee011127
Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay

commit_message:
Fix pylint/astroid breakage

Using test-requirements.txt to pin pylint to 1.4.4 and astroid (a dependency
of pylint) to less than 1.4.0, as newer versions break pylint 1.4.4.

Change-Id: I0e39d88fdcc74f2bfec331d26567a18560fbc3a0

commit_message:
Remove python 2.6 support from python-novaclient

Since oslo is removing support for python 2.6, nova
needs to also remove support from clients and libraries.
This commit is to remove support from python-novaclient.

-- Python 2.6 compatibilty code was removed.
-- Python 2.6 was removed as a tox environment, install venv,
and from the classifiers in setup.cfg.
-- Release notes have been updated.

UpgradeImpact

Co-Authored-By: Andrey Kurilin <andr.kurilin@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I3f587ff38d478d075af5fd014e2b4b8416e185d4
Closes-bug: 1518390

commit_message:
fix grenade jobs for a post-juno world

drop references to juno.

stop running grenade on kilo (as juno is no longer a thing).

consolidate some of the kilo skips under a single run instead of
having a bunch of separate rules.

Change-Id: Ib886951eb6a773f429e51e4fc1ff9fca046c508e

commit_message:
Wait more time after swarm bay creation before doing functional testing

This patch increases waiting loop time after swarm bay creation finished.
Raise a meaningful exception to indicate ca initial failed.

Closes-Bug: #1521395

@Vitaly, Ethan: We are talking about probability. Yes, there is no guarantee that cluster will not be deleted after validation, but there is also no guarantee that it will not be deleted after this ckeck. We can add a bunch of checks of cluster existence during job execution and still have no guaranty. Adding another check is not a fix of the problem. IMO

The only reason to add this check is to make sure that we aren't trying to get status parameter from None. And actually you are right, in this situation it makes sense. But is it the only problem we have? Don't we need to implement the same reference-validation system that we use with many other resources?"}, {'account_id': 9740, 'date': '2015-11-25 15:37:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-25 17:07:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-11-24 08:36:29.000000000', 'message': 'Check when cluster is None

commit_message:
Check cluster if it is None before run job

We should check the return value of conductor.cluster_get(), if
the return value is None, we should return directly.

Change-Id: I55ad18b127798913878fde1d00f4e5ad7b4994c5
Closes-Bug: #1519237

commit_message:
Fix puppet-lint failure

Quoted booleans aren't allowed by puppet-lint, so this removes the
ones that snuck in.

Change-Id: I3cdcca6364476b324249a778d5e75a8befa26dff

commit_message:
Multipath Device Action Being Parsed as Name

Whenever find_multipath_device() was being called on an action
it would include the action as part of the device name. This patch
creates a list of actions and checks that they aren't preceding
the device name before parsing the rest of the device information
in find_multipath_device().

This patch is based on the approach that was taken in Nova until
it was abandoned in favor of the change being made in os-brick
instead. The Change-Id for the Nova change:
I8f1f769bb15ec10054e2fd73c4cf621389014cf1

Change-Id: I12a10ba189e4987cdf07bebdadbac0d4587c01d1
Closes-Bug: 1466444

commit_message:
Fix iopsLimit parameter in ScaleIO connector

The parameter 'iops_limit' in the ScaleIO connector
is wrong. The correct parameter should be 'iopsLimit'.
Because of this error, the iops of the volume will stay
unlimited even if the user sets a limit on the iops.
This patch fixes this error.

Change-Id: I6b9212e9046bf3e2c9bbbde6354c298b359de3a6
Closes-Bug: #1521396

commit_message:
Use KSC auth's register_conf_options instead of oslo.cfg import

A newer keystoneclient is not happy with simply using oslo_config to
import the config group.  Instead, use register_conf_options()
from keystoneclient.auth.

Change-Id: I798dad7ad5bd90362e1fa10c2eecb3e1d5bade71

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from muranoclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: Ibea6301c8c1983b6a2a1e86c15de83b6684ed3d6
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Add network user guide

Add a network user guide to replace the current placeholder.  Also,
add to and update the network examples to go along with the guide.
And finally, add a test for the network examples.

Change-Id: Ib98a7632c3ccc9764a93831f0dbe597ce0bce606
Closes-Bug: #1466186

'}, {'created': '2015-10-01 00:00:48.000000000', 'message': "Add cert tracking and rotating in Housekeeping

The target of this patch is to add the function that once we detect an 
amphora's cert will expire in 2 weeks from utcnow, we will update its
cert with a new one and update its db information at the same time.

In order to achieve this target, I did the following changes:

Add 2 new columns cert_busy and cert_expiration in amphora table
Add methods to get cert expiration date from PEM server_pem and 
update db info
Use the new REST agent method to perform cycling
Add process in housekeeping to facilitate rotation
Add unit tests

This patch depends on the following 2 bugs:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/octavia/+bug/1496634
https://bugs.launchpad.net/octavia/+bug/1496628

Deponds-on: I6ed139e67f2507829dadd82f3adfd99ad6851608
Change-Id: I28578a3e560ee09ba300788a5423863c893b8638

commit_message:
Add cert tracking and rotating in Housekeeping

The goal of this patch is to add the function that once we detect an
amphora's cert will expire in 2 weeks from utcnow, we will update its
cert with a new one and update its db information at the same time.

In order to achieve this target, I did the following changes:

Add 2 new columns cert_busy and cert_expiration in amphora table
Add methods to get cert expiration date from PEM server_pem and
update db info
Use the new REST agent method to perform cycling
Add process in housekeeping to facilitate rotation
Add unit tests

Change-Id: I28578a3e560ee09ba300788a5423863c893b8638

commit_message:
Add '-H -E' options to pass proxy env for sudo

'sudo python /tmp/get-pip.py' command call not working with proxy
env, so add '-H -E' sudo options to pass proxy env to get-pip.py.

Change-Id: If60bacc130d311f7694dba108bf922b393c1017c
Closes-bug: #1519596

commit_message:
Add agent_irmc driver support into os-cloud-config

The agent_irmc driver is already supported by ironic,
so this patch is to add agent_irmc driver into os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: Ieb8c6e2eef96bff4aeef5c46835d56dcdf0834b8

commit_message:
Fix site-packages path for python 2.7

CentOS7 comes with python2.7 included, so we need to
update path to site-packages directory

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Compatible with CentOS6 & CentOS7 master node

Change-Id: Ifa7026ef5e090d740797567e99dae0f08e41c310

commit_message:
Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.
Closes-Bug: 1519510

Change-Id: Ie8dc40df5fddce298f31f7a3d5436493b9b090bb

[{'created': '2015-11-30 22:01:44.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing pep8 failures

Looks like newer pylint is having issues with files. Fixing.

Change-Id: I0e39d88fdcc74f2bfec331d26567a18560fbc3a0
'}, {'created': '2015-12-01 02:03:43.000000000', 'message': "Pinning pylint/astroid versions

Found three issues. First, plylint 1.5.0 identifies new lint errors
that didn't occur before. One of those, is with import ordering,
which it falsely reports that the import for configparser should be
before the import for eventlet, but the configparser import is
inside an if-clause that uses the six module. Moving that up, will
result in an error as six is not imported yet, and moving six up,
gives an ordering warning for six. Will likely need to disable that
warning for this file. In general, we need to asses whether 1.5.0
will work, and will need to revise the code to accomodate this
version.

Second, pylint is not pinned to any version, and can vary at any
time, which can cause a problem, if a newer pylint version has
an issue. Pylint 1.4.4 is used in neutron currently, and was used
in this repo previously.

Third, the astroid package, which is a dependency for pylint,
was updated from 1.3.8 to 1.4.1, which is broken, when used with
pylint 1.4.4 (as is astroid 1.4.0).  A bug has been reported on
astroid upstream. There is no pin for astroid either, unless the
gate-neturon-pep8-constraints job is used (which it is not for this
repo).

This commit does the following, until we can update tools:

- Pin pylint to 1.4.4
- Pin astroid to 1.3.8
- Remove the dependancy from tox.ini, which interferes with any
  pinning in test-requirements.txt
- Addressing some of the errors that were seen with pylint 1.5.0
  (cannot do all, as some changes are incompatible with 1.4.4, like
  the import ordering mentioned above).

Change-Id: I0e39d88fdcc74f2bfec331d26567a18560fbc3a0
"}, {'created': '2015-12-01 15:30:38.000000000', 'message': 'Fix pylint/astroid breakage

Found that pylint 1.5.0 and astroid 1.4.1 generate new errors for pylint
testing. Also, if pin pylint to 1.4.4, which is done in neutron, will have
breakage, because pylint 1.4.4 is not compatible with astroid 1.4.x.

For now, fix is to pin these two in tox.ini to pylint 1.4.4 and astroid
1.3.8.

Later, can implement pep8-constraints job and target for VPN repo, and
that will handle the constraints.

In long term, can migrate to pylint 1.5.0 and resolve the warnings/errors
that crop up. Note: looks like the fixes are not backwards compatible.

Will see if this commit will force pep8 job to use the "right" versions.

Change-Id: I0e39d88fdcc74f2bfec331d26567a18560fbc3a0
'}, {'created': '2015-12-01 19:13:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix pylint/astroid breakage

commit_message:
Fix pylint/astroid breakage

Using test-requirements.txt to pin pylint to 1.4.4 and astroid (a dependency
of pylint) less than 1.4.0. This will resolve current breakage caused by an
incompatible version (1.4.1) of astroid being used with pylint 1.4.4.

Change-Id: I0e39d88fdcc74f2bfec331d26567a18560fbc3a0

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from ganttclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I3ecb1a28a0dcde0c7a95d4aa6efd2dc058fa2dbd
Closes-Bug: 1519510

(0.11.2 and 0.13). The decorator code could be safely deleted once
Horizon migrates to angular-ui/bootstrap v0.13.

commit_message:
Fix for the broken header's dropdowns for both v0.11.2 and v0.13

The dropdownToggle directive from angular-ui/bootstrap v0.11.2
conflicts with the native Bootstrap data-toggle="dropdown" attribute
(see https:github.com/angular-ui/bootstrap/issues/2156). This is fixed
in 0.13, but before that it'd be valuable to ensure that the same html
markup works the same way with both versions of angular-ui/bootstrap
(0.11.2 and 0.13). The decorator code could be safely deleted once
Horizon migrates to angular-ui/bootstrap v0.13.

Also fix dropdowns in material theme templates.

Closes-Bug: #1466146
Change-Id: I8f01c1ce7b0a5dc29bf9d8aba23c9ea7e6e1ec35

commit_message:
Fix Download get-pip play in vagrant.yml

Fixes syntax for get_url module in ansible playbook vagrant.yml
which was causing the vagrant up command to fail.

Change-Id: Iffb0b17c8f808b33538b06d21c52ca603f018a9c
Closes-Bug: 1521750

[{'created': '2015-11-30 17:45:32.000000000', 'message': '[microversions] Increase max version to 2.7

2.7 - Check the is_public attribute of a flavor before adding tenant
access to it. Reject the request with HTTPConflict error.

Since novaclient already have Conflict expection, there is no required
changes on client side.

Change-Id: I48dca20b3795185363367bac0e2ee65ce938593f
'}]
commit_message:
[microversions] Increase max version to 2.7

2.7 - Check the is_public attribute of a flavor before adding tenant
access to it. Reject the request with HTTPConflict error.

Since novaclient already have Conflict expection, there is no required
changes on client side.

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 330, 'name': 'John Dickinson', 'email': 'me@not.mn', 'username': 'notmyname'}, {'_account_id': 597, 'name': 'Pete Zaitcev', 'email': 'zaitcev@kotori.zaitcev.us', 'username': 'zaitcev'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 6316, 'name': 'Anita Kuno', 'email': 'anteaya@anteaya.info', 'username': 'anteaya'}, {'_account_id': 6547, 'name': 'Andreas Jaeger', 'email': 'jaegerandi@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaegerandi'}, {'_account_id': 6968, 'name': 'Christian Schwede', 'email': 'cschwede@redhat.com', 'username': 'cschwede'}, {'_account_id': 7847, 'name': 'Alistair Coles', 'email': 'alistairncoles@gmail.com', 'username': 'acoles'}, {'_account_id': 9216, 'name': 'Joel Wright', 'email': 'joel.wright@gmail.com', 'username': 'jjw-sohonet'}, {'_account_id': 15343, 'name': 'Tim Burke', 'email': 'tburke@nvidia.com', 'username': 'tburke'}]

[{'account_id': 16352, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:08:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:15:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-project-config-layout http://logs.openstack.org/08/252308/1/check/gate-project-config-layout/3c89704/ : SUCCESS in 4m 31s'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-12-02 12:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

We did agree to drop py26 support.

The plan was to cut a final 2.6 release first.

Unfortunately the irc meeting log got truncated [1] but in my scrollback I have a record of the decision:


  <openstack> Meeting started Wed Nov 18 21:00:30 2015 UTC and is due to finish in 60 minutes.  The chair is notmyname. Information about MeetBot at http://wiki.debian.org/MeetBot.

[snip]

<notmyname> last week we talked about py26 in swiftclient
<notmyname> or specifically the fact that -infra is dropping testing support for py26
<travisn> o/
<notmyname> here's what I propose: we drop support for py26 (and also do a major version bump to indicate that). if someone is still dependent on a distro using py26, they should contact their distro for support about packages that have moved on
<notmyname> what do you think?
<joeljwright> sounds good to me
<mattoliverau> sounds good
<joeljwright> there are multiple options for rhel6 based distros
<torgomatic> no complaints here
<mattoliverau> if we can't test it, then we can't support it
<cschwede> mattoliverau: fully agree!
<notmyname> mattoliverau: very true
<notmyname> the other option would be for someone to step up with 3rd party CI for py26
<notmyname> however, 3rd party jobs aren't voting in the gate
<joeljwright> I think there are enough good options
<joeljwright> and good reasons not to use py26
<notmyname> so we *could* do it in the community QA cluster. but I don't think we should
<joeljwright> softwarecollections and uis both have python27 parallel installables for rhel6 based distros
<mattoliverau> I think its fine to drop, we dropped it in the server about a release ago, the client staggers a release.. so lets drop it.
<notmyname> does anyone want to fight for keeping py26 support in swiftclient?
<notmyname> mattoliverau: I think there's a wider base for the client than for the server. most client users shouldn't care what's in the server
<notmyname> ok
<mattoliverau> that's true, but its nice for us developers to have a similar code base for both (or no crazy hacks) :P
<notmyname> #agreed drop support for py26 in python-swiftclient
<notmyname> of course the actual final "agreement" for that will be the patches in gerrit
<notmyname> so here's the plan: we'll likely need to do a final 2.x series release with py26 support. then we'll do a 3.0 release without py26
<notmyname> those don't have to be one right after each other, but they should probably be relatively close
<notmyname> I'll check on the -infra side to get actual dates for py26 tests
<notmyname> and go from there

[snip]


[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/swift/2015/swift.2015-11-18-21.00.log.txt'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-12-02 12:50:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,

Closes-Bug: 1519510
"}]
commit_message:
Remove py26 support from swiftclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I37116731db11449d0c374a6a83a3a43789a19d5f
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Add useful 'time_it' decorator

Create a helpful decorator that can be attached to functions
or methods to show how long they take to run; internally it
uses a stop watch and provided logger to log with (and an
optional logging level to use).

An example:

>>> from oslo_utils import timeutils
>>> import logging
>>> import time
>>> logging.basicConfig(level=logging.DEBUG)
>>> logger = logging.getLogger()
>>>
>>> @timeutils.time_it(logger)
... def a():
...   time.sleep(0.2)
...
>>> a()
DEBUG:root:It took 0.20 seconds to run function '__main__.a'

Change-Id: Ia41d5b6910f7ebe2dd93aaf6ca1defe158f8310c

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from heatclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I745d671fa5092fb5b796b18674e21dab1991643c
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from kiteclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: Ie6bd472cb3d2947bb5b9e1fec982a65cfced624e
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Moving exception specification

Horizon defines classes of exception from the services it
communicates with. In the plugin case, the plugin needs to set
up including plugin content specific exceptions to the classes of
exceptions in Horizon. This patch includes this content.

Setting up an extensible exception list in exceptions.py and
including the exceptions in the configuration files.

Change-Id: Ie91cfe1e0f34a710a96b4a43cf62af35d989920c

commit_message:
Ipv4 DHCP support without running the DHCP agent

We fully support distributed Ipv4 DHCP, if the deployment
is IPv4 only no need for the dhcp agent it could be removed
from the installation. the plugin will take care of the
DHCP server port creation.

In case the deployment use IPv6 the dhcp agent need to be
installed and the neutron server need to be configured
with additional variable.

use_centralized_ipv6_DHCP=True

This extra setting could be removed once we implement
the Ipv6 distributed DHCP SDN application

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from glanceclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I53de6c93d8fd3a5e7afd57bbeb175a91becd2e3f
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Move type formatting from generator to type

This change moves the formatting for each type into each class for that
type. Each type now has control over its own formatting rather than
being under the generators purview. This allows developers to create
their own types in their project and set its it's own formatting.
Refactoring the layout this way also makes it easier to create new types
and update existing types. Another benefit could be that outputting the
config can be detached from the generator which is specifically for
generating config files.

Change-Id: I7cf94a1b2cbbfe67282e8a157548caff825d2811

[{'created': '2015-12-02 15:58:58.000000000', 'message': "Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.
Closes-Bug: 1519510

Change-Id: I2f9a6961fcddda543d484fcfd12a51dbb536d517
"}]
commit_message:
Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.
Closes-Bug: 1519510

Change-Id: I2f9a6961fcddda543d484fcfd12a51dbb536d517

commit_message:
[install] do not use swift password between ""  or ''.

An error occurs when you use a password for the user swift (in keystone)
between "" or '' in /etc/swift/proxy-server.conf.

backport: kilo
Closes-Bug: #1487051

Change-Id: I83f79e3f7a1eac0b39827c751e4de1ced4049619

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from designateclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I479081c88b53175def2a5ea06ee1d3435ed6444e
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from cinderclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I6f9f7dcb4e454f4d1e12943a1f4a1ab3ced0eba3
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Remove py26 jobs from manilaclient

Support of py26 is going to be dropped in CI and already is dropped
in manilaclient dependencies. So, remove this job from manilaclient.

Change-Id: Ia6b8fdc6ef53235fef1be07c3deb05b0d9117878
Related-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Fix delete quota of subprojects

This patch aims to fix the bug in which cinder raises
an error when performing a delete quota operation in
a subproject.

Steps to reproduce:
- Create a project A in keystone (e.g openstack project create A);
- Create a project B in keystone with A as its parent (e.g openstack
  project create B --property parent_id=<id of project A>);
- Update the quota value of A (e.g. openstack quota set
  <id of project A> --volume 5)
- Update the quota value of B (e.g. openstack quota set
  <id of project B> --volume 2)
- Try to delete the quota of B (e.g. cinder quota-delete
  <id of project B>)

Change-Id: Id1a749433c3679f1b2adf87ea0a280366c5e4a15
Closes-bug: #1496058

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from python-neutronclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I4a2f860e8138bddb032418ee555e07a6fa0a3f3e
Closes-Bug: 1519510

Forgot the vote for the current code.( Test is still a good value add though_)'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-11-23 19:24:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Reedip, I'm not sure what you mean. The neutron API ignores parameters that don't exist so it will still return all ports if you provide a name filter."}, {'account_id': 17776, 'date': '2015-11-24 01:00:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Kevin: I thought that the parse_args_to_dict function in neutron client infact adds all the extra command options and sends it to the Neutron Server.
That has been the cause of several issues in NeutronClient in the past.
The current implementation of Neutron Client  ( for show, delete, update etc) is that it tries to search for something using find_resourceid_by_name_or_id function.
Now if the attribute passed is an ID, then it returns one row ( because ID is a unique property).
If the attribute passed is not an ID, neutronclient assumes it to be a name, and searches based on the ŃAME field( and uses the find_resource_by_name function)
If the name field doesnt exist, then it returns all the information because the Neutron Server is not able to parse based on the NAME filed( as it doesnt exist).

I guess this is the reason why the current code requires a change, for which this patch was introduced.
If yes, then the following tests can be incorporated:
- Pass an ID and see if the returned result is correct or not.( Kind of a regression test..)
- Pass an attribute which is neither Name nor ID and see if there is NO entry returned now ( previously it returned all entries).'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-24 03:49:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

@reedip, neutronclient unit tests have no knowledge on neutron API itself,
so I don't think we can test it at the level of unit tests. It can be tested only by CLI functional tests. However, this kind of tests do not exist in the current code tree. You can freely improve the functional tests to cover this kind of problems. I don't think we need to block this change."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-24 03:49:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Do not allow name lookups on RBAC policies

RBAC policies have no name field so the name query to
the server was always returning all entries since the
name filter was ignored.

This corrects the behavior by disabling the name lookup
for RBAC policies.

Change-Id: I6c5afa05cefb1709e9667a1aaf20105c707dc95c
Closes-Bug: #1517818

commit_message:
Put py34 first in the env order of tox

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34
we have to run first the py34 env to, then, run py27. This patch
puts py34 first on the tox.ini list of envs to avoid this problem
to happen.
Closes-bug: #1489059
Change-Id: I9d3a79b865d7f3d86eca8f8dcaee598bbd917c19

commit_message:
Add murano service broker to Fuel WEB

This patch add support of newly introduced murano service called
murano cfapi to Fuel UI.

Implements: bp implement-support-for-murano-service-broker
Change-Id: Ifc8a3861d82af13765cd0759de1846b431f057e9

Going forward, we'll be performing a ton of version checks within manila_tempest_tests:

I understand we can't reference a class within manila itself. We should have a helper definition exclusively here.

And wherever necessary, we should:
0) Always accept micro version as a string
1) Split the micro version into major and minor portions.
3) Either use the ComparableMixin (make a copy from manila/utils: https://github.com/openstack/manila/blob/b4611145/manila/utils.py)

or, 
3) Perform comparison on major version and then,
4) Perform comparison on minor version. 

 https://github.com/openstack/manila/blob/b4611145/manila/api/openstack/api_version_request.py

I opened a bug against existing code: https://bugs.launchpad.net/manila/+bug/1518996

'}, {'created': '2015-10-30 13:04:13.000000000', 'message': 'Add new URLs for APIs ported from extensions

After port of extensions to core API we need to rename its URLs.

So, rename URLs and bump microversion for it.
Make new URls work only with new microversion(s) 2.7+
and old with old microversions 1.0-2.6.
Add separate API router for v2 API as now we should split v1 and v2
logic.
Also, move updated APIs under v2 directory that will be used by both
API routers - v1 and v2.

List of updated URLs is following:

+----------------------+---------------------+
|     Old (1.0-2.6)    |      New (2.7+)     |
+----------------------+---------------------+
| os-availability-zone |  availability-zones |
+----------------------+---------------------+
|      os-services     |       services      |
+----------------------+---------------------+
|     os-quota-sets    |      quota-sets     |
+----------------------+---------------------+
|  os-quota-class-sets |   quota-class-sets  |
+----------------------+---------------------+

Partially implements bp ext-to-core

Change-Id: I82f00114db985b4b3bf4db0a64191559508ac600
